data.value: All cards in MTG have specific card types that interact differently. The first thing that should be noted is that all cards being played except for lands are considered spells while being played. For the top of the list the two card types that will always remain spells even after having resolved are instants and sorceries, once these cards are successfully played they are moved into the graveyard. The next type of cards is permanents, which are cards that once are played remain on the battlefield until removed by another effect, in which case they are moved to the graveyard. All the permanent types are artifact, creature, enchantment, land, planeswalker, and battle(the current image does not have battle since it is relatively new). Sometimes card types can intertwine such as an artifact creature for example, which means that it is both types at the same time and is affected by cards that specify either type. The Misc category is for card types that mainly have to do with different ways of playing the game, and for the most part aren’t relevant in typical play. The only exception to this is the tribal tag, which typically now comes combined with spells of the other permanent types. Obsolete are card types that have been changed since the creation of the game to fit into another card type to make more sense. Interrupts have been changed to instants, mana sources have been changed to lands and or permants where applicable. Moving into Supertypes the Obsolete supertypes are typically just not printed onto cards anymore or have been moved into existing categories, and on the same note it is also a similar circumstance to the world supertype that used to exist for enchantments. The only Supertypes that are typically in play currently are Legendary which means that only one copy of that legendary card can be in play under your side of the field at a time, Basic denoting one of the five basic land types that you can use any number of, and Snow which is a variety of card/land they made for a handful of sets. Subtypes typically are printed after the main type of card and come into play typically on cards that specifically play with those given subtypes.
